Psammobia Risso, 1826 [Histoire naturelle des principales productions de l'Europe méridionale, 4: 375] is listed in Neave, 1940, Nomenclator Zoologicus, 3: 953, as a separate entry; Risso used Psammobia twice, in the family Nymphacées (p. 350) and in the family Les solens (p. 375), without indicating whether he intended to establish a new name; for the latter, see Psammosolen. QUALIFICATION: as stated by Keen, 1969, [in Moore, ed.] Treatise on invertebrate paleontology, N2: 637; Solenocurtis [Swainson, 1840, A treatise on malacology: 366], Solenocurtus [Sowerby, 1842, A conchological manual, ed. 2: 262], Solenicurtus [W. Clark, 1851, Annals and Magazine of Natural History, ser. 2, 8: 471, 473], and Solencurtus [Coppi, 1881, Paleontologia modenese: 112] are incorrect subsequent spellings. Cyrtosolen was suggested by Herrmannsen, 1848, Indicis generum malacozoorum primordia, 2: 468, to be a more proper spelling, but it was not used as valid and is not an available name. See also Solenocurtus P. Fischer. Agassiz, 1839, Mémoires de la Société des Sciences Naturelles de Neuchâtel, 2: 42, 43, designated Solen caribaeus as type species, but this was not an originally included species. Solecurtus Agassiz [non Blainville, 1824], 1839 is listed in Neave, 1940, Nomenclator Zoologicus, 4: 218, as a separate entry, but is merely a misapplication of Solecurtus Blainville. Senior objective synonym of Macha Oken, 1835

PUB_PUB_FORMATTED: Huber, M. 2010. Lajonkairia digitale (E.A. Smith, 1916). Bouchet, P.; Gofas, S.; Rosenberg, G. (2010) World Marine Mollusca database. World Register of Marine Species. Accessed on 2011-11-15. http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=507461

QUALIFICATION: Bouchet lists the valid name 'Lamarck [ex Leach MS] 1818 Histoire naturelle des animaux sans vertèbres, 5: 543; Introduced in synonymy, but treated as valid before 1960. Mysia T. Brown, 1827 [Illustrations of the conchology of Great Britain and Ireland: pl. 16] and Mysia Wood, 1840 [The Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 6: 250] are listed by Sherborn and Neave as separate names. In the index (p. ii), Brown attributed Mysia to Leach, and Wood also refered to Leach, so it is clear that both Lamarck, Brown and Wood used the same name, although with different taxonomic extensions; Tellina rotundata Montagu [Ungulinidae] was the only species included in Mysia by Brown, and Wood included Mysia ornata Wood, 1840 and Venus undata
